title: For Sale:  Bulgarian Makarov with LOTS of extras: price reduced, pics added
postcontent:
This is a "Makarov Arsenal" Bulgarian Makarov chambered in 9 X 18 and it is in beautiful condition.  This is not one of those CAI Maks with the crude engraving on the slide, no, the fit and finish on this one is better than many of the East German Maks I've seen.  Importer is K&G, and the slide was reblued over the stamp.  This pistol appears to be in "like new" excellent condition.

I have a lot of extras to go with this piece.

First, I believe I have an example of almost every grip ever made for the Makarov, including custom grips.  They are as follows:

1. Custom hand carved checkered rosewood grip, which are on the piece now.
2. The impossible to find rubberized "Mak-a-wrap" grip made in limited quantites for the folks at Makarov.com about a decade ago.
3. The highly desirable black plastic East German grip, with the proper screw.
4. The red bakelite Soviet grip with lanyard ring.
5.  The thick black rubber Pearce grip.

That is 5 sets of grips with extra screws.

I also have THREE 8-rd magazines and a custom suede leather pocket holster to go with the Makarov.

And then there is the ammunition.  I'm guessing about 450 rounds of it:

13 rds Glaser Silver 75 gr prefragmented defense ammo
100 rds Federal 90 gr JHP
29 rds super hot Barnaul 95 gr JHP
150 rds Silver Bear 94 gr JHP
70 rds Winchester Metric 95 gr FMJ (for use at indoor ranges with ammo restrictions)
50 rds Brown Bear 94 gr FMJ
40 rds Barnaul 94 gr FMJ

I paid 325 for the Makarov last year and it was unfired by the prior owner.  I have put exactly 25 rounds down the pipe and it functioned flawlessly.  I paid about 200 for the extra grips, 45 for the extra mags, 30 for the holster, and around 300 for the ammo, so I'm figuring I've got about 900 into the entire package.

The Makarov is considered to be perhaps the most reliable and durable pistol ever made -- far more so than the Walther PP from which the Soviets developed their design.  It is DA/SA with a decocker, takedown is simple, and the capacity is 8 + 1.  The 9 X 18 round is more powerful than the 380 and can be made almost as hot as the 9mm parabellum.  This is a great opportunity to acquire a very nice Bulgie with rare ammo and rare grips 

I would like to trade for a Star BM 9mm, but may consider other compact single stack 9mm pistols or a 38 J-frame.  The only double stack 9mm I have any interest in would be a 469.  Would gladly accept boxes of quality 9mm ammunition as a partial trade (no Wolf, Prvi, or reloads).  Cash price reduced to $380.

Pics are up at the following site:

http://www.co-ar15.com/forums/showthread.php?t=21742

title: For Sale:  S&W M&P15T w/Optics, ammo, and lots of upgrades!
postcontent:
Well, I'm about to do what I said I'd never do......list my AR for sale. I've always said my safe has a revolving door, but this was the only gun without a price tag. Then I decided I wanted to get back into motocross and a badass CRF450R presented itself today! So here it is....my baby.

It's a S&W M&P15T. In case you're not aware, many AR aficionados rank the M&P series of rifles among the best. There are many articles you can Google, as I did before deciding this was the one I wanted. Here is a list of goodies, both from the factory and what I've added:

    * Troy Industries Front and Rear BUIS (Factory Installed)
    * Troy Industries Mid-length Rail with Covers (Factory Installed)
    * Magpul Moe Grip (original included as well)
    * Magpul Enhanced Trigger Guard
    * 3 Magpul Windowed PMAG's with Ranger Base Plates
    * Vortex Flash Hider (original A2 birdcage included as well)
    * Larue Tactical SPR-1.5 style Scope Mount (rock solid!)
    * Vector Optics FFP 1-4x24 Scope with Dual Illuminated Mil-Dot Reticle
    * Badger Tactical Charging Handle Latch
    * Vertical Fore Grip (Blackhawk, I think)

In all, I have well over $2000 into this rifle. It is 100% without flaw, as it's been in a padded case since new. This has literally been babied. I bought right after "Dear Leader" was inaugurated, but it was soon enough before the price gouging started. I'll probably regret selling this the instant someone says "I'll take it", but I can always (hopefully) get another one. I can tell you that when I do buy another AR, it will be identical to this one! Although I've only fired 270 rounds through it, I've fired enough other brands of AR's to quickly realize how good mine is. I won't compare it to Noveske or LMT or some of the other boutique manufacturers, as they're in a league of their own. You also pay much more for them.

Anyhow, here it is. I'm open to shipping from FFL to FFL or FTF if you're in the Pittsburgh area. If feedback is a concern, I have great feedback on eBay under the same screen name. I'll go to whatever lengths necessary to ensure buyer confidence. Email me and I'll give you my phone number and we can discuss further.

Asking price is $1800 OBO for the package. This includes about 500 rounds of Federal brass ammo and a tactical carry case that's in the picture. I'm also open to $1700 shipped to your FFL for everything, less the ammo. I also have the factory hard case and cardboard box it came in, as well as all documentation. I'd say, conservatively, that this package is worth about $2200, if purchased new. I'm pretty firm on the price, as I honestly don't want to sell it.

If you have any questions or would like specific photos, email me and I'll get back to you.

title: For Sale/Trade:  .38 Ruby Extra revolver 4" barrel
postcontent:
It is either a cheap Smith and Wesson knock off or a well made foriegn pistol, you decide!

This is a Ruby Extra from the late fifties or early sixties. It is a good shooter and accurate ...but... the blue was bad so it is polished up (bare steel) now. It is a .38 and I would NOT run +P through this. I have used "cowboy loads" very successfully. It has decent lock up and a good feel in the hand. It should be a very dependable and accurate pistol but also have a  low price and virtually no collector value. It does have the original parts and grips. Note it also it has the hammer block safety system and working mechanisim of a Smith and Wesson, thus its reliability. So, yes it will safely load and carry 6 shots of .38 stopping power. But alas it is a Ruby and not a Smith so it has a low price. The perfect piece for the night table or for the occasional shooter. I am open to trade but would show preference to a cash deal. I had 2 of these but found them to be pretty good shooters so my Dad (he's 81) now has the other at his place, so yes I have faith in them for defensive use. Questions call Craig at REDACTED before 9 PM please.

title: For Sale/Trade:  38 snubnose revolver s&w model 38
postcontent:
I dont know much about this gun. I bought it from a friend a few months back. I tryed it at a firing range and did not care for it. This is my first gun. I was looking to do a possible trade for a 9mm that takes a clip, but would be willing to sell it. I didnt care much for the revolver part and it does not have a saftey switch. Im looking for something with a saftey. Prefer a trade.

All I can tell you is what I was told about it. The friend said that they thought it was made in the 1960's and that he didnt think they were made anymore. It belonged to his father-in-laws best friend that had passed away and that is how it came to be sold. I have included pictures and if you need better pictures or numbers off of it email me.

I paid $400 for it and would like to get that much out of it. 

UPDATE - I found this info on the web if it helps. It's a model 38

The Smith & Wesson Model 38/49 "Bodyguard" is a Model 36 that has a "Camel Hump" hammer shroud used to prevent clothing snag, as the hammer is concealed in the shroud. The Smith & Wesson Bodyguard was unusual in that the alloy framed "Airweight" was released to the public first as the Smith & Wesson Airweight Bodyguard in 1955. In 1957 Smith & Wesson changed the named to the Model 38. When they released the version with the steel frame, they renamed the gun again, to the Model 49 in 1959. So the early alloy framed revolvers are usually the Model 38 and the Steel framed versions are the Model 49.

location: Wood River, IL (by St. Louis), Illinois, United States
postcontent:
What I have is an Early CETME .308 battle rifle.  The CETME was designed by the Spanish and later ripped off by the Germans to create their G3 or HK 91 rifles.  This model was imported and placed on a Century Arms receiver (because all the dumb import laws.)  There are many variations in the CETME rifles.  Some are junk but others are excellent rifles.  The one I have for sale is a well made rifle.  It has a solid stainless steel cast receiver...not the sheet metal stamp job that you'll see on most.  It has wood furniture, and has been stained and lacquered to make it look very nice.  All the Metal on this weapon matches (another rare trait on CETMEs).
I have 3-20rnd mags, and 1-30rnd mag.  Also have a B-Square scope mount (very solid).

I've lowered my asking price to $600.  I'm mostly trying to sell the rifle but I will consider the following for trades.

I'm interested in a nice flat top AR upper receiver. specifically: 1-7 twist chrome lined threaded barrel.  Receiver must be mat black.

I'm also interested in .45 ACP pistols.  American made brands only.  Wanting something accurate with good sights.

I can send more detailed pictures of individual parts if you would be interested.  Only defect is some wear in the receiver just behind the ejection port from the brass bouncing off the side.
